# MoonDAO B2B: Final Report

[MoonDAO Final Report Reference](https://docs.google.com/document/d/16F-_bcC0C4889YmuQl6WWChDKQObHhmfjasDna0wOmk/edit?usp=sharing)

## Summary

## **Goal:** The objective of the project team was to establish a foundational framework for MoonDAO’s Decentralized Sales Structure, allowing every MoonDAO member to contribute to the mission through DAO to Business or DAO to DAO engagements. The MoonDAO B2B project was active from the 6th of June to the 14th of August.Subsequently, the project team was dissolved by Astronaut Pablo Moncada, and as a result, no further B2B activities were pursued. The contributions of this project to MoonDAO’s standing in the DeSci ecosystem are significant, addressing and capitalizing on opportunities that might have been overlooked. Challenges encountered included a lack of clarity from MoonDAO senate members on the potential achievements of a MoU and the availability of resources to form competent project teams aligned with community interests. Legal uncertainties due to delays with the MiDAO entity were also a concern but have since been resolved.Lucasart, a key member of the project, departed during the coordination and documentation phases, followed by Mitchie, who exited after developing the inbound onboarding form. Manuel, along with Tyler and Luigi, managed the remaining B2B team responsibilities, focusing on outreach and refining the proposal process from initial contact to MoU creation.Currently, MoonDAO is not engaging in any external, coordinated outreach or partnership initiatives, foregoing potential opportunities to make a greater impact in the Web3 and Space industry.<!--StartFragment-->**Summary**The MoonDAO Partnerships framework (then renamed MoonDAO B2B) had an identity crisis at its inception. The proposal was written by Pablo to be an inbound framework for getting MoonDAO to approve partnership opportunities that came our way. However, there was another vision for how it should operate as a “decentralized sales structure” which was the initial goal. Subsequently the two visions were never aligned after many conversations about how to operate the project. After trying to intervene by some of the initial members of the team to fulfill the initial goals of the project with the inbound pipeline, the project continued on the direction of the initial proposal, Lucas dropped out. Followed by the departure of Mitchie as well after delivering on the inbound framework he agreed to during the proposal creation. Pablo shut down the project after two of the three initial members dropped out, and 4 MOUs had been submitted to the Senate after two months of the project.
